segments.text: Rick Reynolds came up and put his hand over my shoulder and said, well, he'd been crying, but he said, now you've got something to tell your older brother about.
You made it.
And you feel a relief and a true elation because now you realize you're an upperclassman.
And, of course, when you get back the fall of your sophomore year, you realize you're not much of an upperclassman.
But a lot of elation.
And so you go home.
How, at the end of that freshman year?
Near as I remember.
My mother came and picked me up.
I don't recall much about the trip home.
I'd torn my knee, my ACL and medial meniscus in the fall playing intramural football, and so I went home for knee surgery.
and was operated.
Then I spent, after I recovered, went on to work the second half of summer up in Colorado.
And so things were a little foggy back then, but I just get my knee repaired and go on.
Having had the knee injury, I ended up
through my freshman and the rest of my sophomore year, doing special weight training for my legs with Emil Mammoliga was over, and a wonderful guy, neat guy, and I really got a lot out of that.
Met some wonderful people there in the athletic department, and they were very, very nice to me.

Someone, I guess he took me in, he had a class of jocks in some sort of kinesiology or something and was explaining knee injuries and so had me stand up on a desk and demonstrate what had happened and what the procedure was that fixed my knee and that sort of thing.
Did you become acquainted with the quack shack during those days?
I did.
Got the flu one time, felt bad somewhere during that year and went and realized that the guys that were in there were a lot sicker than me and I didn't want to stay.
and hobbled over there the day after I'd torn my knee up, and it was swollen, and that's about where we were at that time.
It was a quack shack, and it was not a whole lot to be done.
Do you remember who the docs were?
Don't remember.
Where was the surgery done?
The surgery was done in Midland.
In Midland, okay.
Yeah, it was done with Dad being a general surgeon.
One of his colleagues, Dr. Thurston Dean, repaired my knee.
As you get here as a sophomore, what was it like in your outfit to be a
a sophomore?
Well, we were pretty fired up and we were ready to go.

We had a lot of freshmen coming in and you're full of piss and vinegar and you're ready to be an upperclassman and it didn't take too long when the orders started coming down and you didn't perform to realize that you were still a freshman in many ways.
We had our, oh I guess
what are you, squad leaders, I guess.
I was a squad leader.
There were many of my buddies.
And you start working your freshman.
But this was a wonderful time, because you start meeting new people.
They're in your outfit.
And you're the enemy, because you're the upperclassmen.
And you can't fraternize with them in your own outfit.
But I had a few of kindred spirit that shared some of the hunting and fishing things.
And it wasn't long, and you learn to close the door.
OK, guys, let's talk.
And one of them was Mike Streetman, who owns Garcia's Cafe here now.
Mike Bell, who's a pilot for Southwest Airlines, we've run into each other.
Back when we were in the Air Force, we'd run into each other.
Yeah, it was an upper class, but it was a little bit different as a sophomore.
It's not near as meaningful as your freshman year, there's no way.
You can't have near the memories, and you have a lot more pressure.
And academically, you never thought about changing majors?
I never did.
Vet school was my focus because we felt that, both my parents and myself,
a degree in veterinary medicine would give me the broadest base to do something in the natural sciences.
I wasn't fixed on being a private clinical practitioner, but vet school was my goal.
And that was my big goal during my sophomore year, and I almost didn't make it.
I went core happy, and I got really hit up with being an upperclassman and being a sharp cadet, and grades suffered for the first time.
Yeah, they went down.
So I did better as a freshman than I did as a sophomore.
And I posted a, I think it was like a 3.1 or a 3.2 the fall semester of my sophomore year.
And so that got my attention.
And I'd run into my first difficult, truly hard class, and that was organic chemistry.
For me, it was difficult.
I didn't enjoy it.
I hated the labs.
And I was telling Kyle earlier, we walked by the chemistry building.
I was in an organic chemistry lab.
One of the upperclassmen in my outfit, a junior, was in that class, had not done well.
He had been trying to get into, had a professional degree plan but was not doing well and had done something, not really wrong, but to irk his Chinese lab instructor.
And the Chinese lab instructor said he was going to fail him.
And he said, I've done everything right.
And he said, no, you know, and he was duty bound.
He was going to give him an F. And this upperclassman, and I can't remember his name, but I can remember it like it was yesterday, grabbed that
lab instructor and held him out of the four-story window in the chemistry department, told him he was either, you pass me or I drop you.
And Kyle asked me, I don't remember what came of that, but I know the upperclassman didn't get kicked out of school, so I guess he survived that deal, but he literally held him out of the window.
Today there'd be a lawsuit.
Oh, sure, sure, sure.
He'd be dead.
Now, did you go to vet school after two years?
After two years.
You were gung-ho for the Corps your second year, did your extracurricular life
change that second year in terms of dates and social life and everything?
No, my girlfriend, we broke up that fall.
She was at Baylor, and that was the end of that.
We still didn't have any wheels, so some things didn't really change.

Sophomore wasn't really a whole lot different being a freshman, and had dates with other girls would come down from different places, and they start realizing there's a whole new world out there, and a number of wonderful young ladies from
Houston, Dallas, wherever, but no real change there.
Where did you and your buddies go on a Saturday night to have a good time?
Well, sophomores were still underage.
There wasn't really, I remember back then there was probably four barbecue joints and about four or five beer joints, and that was it, and we were underage.
And I was a year younger than them, so, boy, there wasn't much.
Did you all go to the clay pits?
Well, I can remember...
Of course, Whiskey Bridge, I remember going to the river.
This is one thing we didn't talk about.
Back at the start as a freshman, every year we'd have an outfit beer bust on the Brazos River.

The upperclassmen would buy beer for the freshmen, and, of course, you piled into cars and went out there, and you had basically a fire, and everybody sat around drinking beer because there wasn't anything else to do.
Typically, two or three of the freshmen would get so drunk they'd throw up in one of the upperclassmen's cars, and that was part of it.

usually cold so they would have to worry about anybody well one year we had people swim the river back and back and forth and didn't lose anybody um did that every year and uh and there was beer and whiskey what were people smoking then there's no marijuana in our deal did you even know the word did because it it existed i hadn't been around it in high school uh just missed it i guess and
There had been somebody caught with marijuana a year or two before I got into squadron six.
One guy had had some, but it just wasn't that, it wasn't commonplace.
It existed, you heard about it, you heard about some of the non-regs, some of the civilian students, but it wasn't an issue.
You gotta remember, I was in a pre-vet, primarily ag outfit.
These were country boys.
And hadn't heard of heroin?
No, no, hard drugs, narcotics were not an issue.
And there really wasn't a wild place around here.
Not anywhere close to here.
There was the Lakeway Club, and the guys that got mobile, they might go out there up in North Bryan, a country western place.
But that's pretty well it, because drinking laws and whatnot, there was no public place to go.
Did you go to any religious activities?
Was a Christian, am a Christian, was a Christian at the time, but didn't have any major push to go anywhere.
There was a little Episcopal chapel just south of the core area, and that was within walking distance.
And I'd gone to an Episcopal day school
No, seventh and eighth grade, I think.
And so I would go sporadically and enjoyed a pretty neat little congregation, neat little fellowship.
But I wasn't a regular attender by any means.
Was Bill Oxley the minute?
Yes, he was.
Bill Oxley, that's exactly right.
He's now deceased, but I saw his wife last Sunday night at one of my faculty colleagues, Vic Treat's grandson was baptized and Mary was there.
All right.
Reverend Oxley, I can remember, I wasn't even Episcopalian, but he always had a twinkle in his eye.
He was a neat guy, neat fella.
Let's see, you applied for vet school your sophomore year?
Sophomore year.
Describe all of that routine.
Well, it's sweaty palms time.
You go through, you fill out the stuff, you make your application, was granted an interview, so go over in uniform like everything else.
When I go into my

interview Mad Dog Davis was there Dr. John Miliff neuroanatomy professor let's see Ken Davis clinical pathologist was there and maybe one other and when I walked in the room Dr. Miliff said where'd you learn how to shine your shoes
and they had a good spit shine and I said, that's kind of what we do.
So they want to talk about the Corps and these were old guard fellows and they were fine.
And I'm thinking this is looking pretty good.
And then they asked me about one of my letters of recommendation of which you've written me one, you probably don't remember.
They didn't ask about that, but they got one from Dad Orson, Midland, Texas, one of their classmates.
whom they had thought had been killed when the Japanese troop transport was torpedoed in World War II, had no idea that Dr. Orson was still alive.
He didn't practice.
He was a rancher in Midland.
And until they got that letter, they had no idea.
So that was neat, and they really wanted to know all about him.
And so I'm really happy about this.
I am great.
I'm in.
I can't lose.
And then...
Dr. Davis throws out my organic chemistry F that I had at midterm.
He says, what about this?
I said, oh, that was at midterm.
We're already up to a C and we're looking good.
But he said, by God, it better be.
Well, I ended up getting accepted.
And then my final grades came out and I had a D in organic chemistry.
Because once I was accepted, I could care less.
And with a letter from Al Price, the dean at the time of the vet school, that although it is passing, we strongly recommend that you retake it.
And I read into it, strongly recommend, didn't say require.
So I was off to Colorado the next day for two and a half months working in the mountains.
But until I was accepted, you sweat bullets because a number of people, of course, applied to get into vet school.
Had over 900 applicants that year.

And the weekend that my letter came, got my mail over at the MSC, had my little mailbox, and you'd go by and you'd look daily, and there'd be nothing in it, and maybe a letter from home, maybe nothing.
That was before the days of junk mail and credit cards.
And there's a letter in from the vet school that says congratulations, and boy, I was just on cloud nine.
Had two of my buddies that were sitting restrictions that weekend for some sin they'd committed, and they found out, and they jumped up and down.
They were so excited.
We took off.
The rest of the guys were down.
There was a group that went down to Hudgens Ramen Breeders down around Hungerford in the Horton area.
Some of them had dates down there.
And we found them at a dance hall that night somewhere in that part of the world.
The guys were sitting restrictions.
I guess, I don't know how many restrictions they had to sit after that, because they just bugged out and went with them.
And we had somebody that got a case of beer, and we celebrated all the way down and back.
You said about 900 applicants.
How many were admitted?
Okay.
And so you must have had a number of friends who were admitted and a number who were not here on campus.
Out of the core, yeah, I did.
A number on the campus, quite a high percentage that were pre-vet, that were in the Honors Colloquium, I think were accepted.
Of course, a lot of vet students come from other schools.
In my outfit, three of us were accepted.
Two, Allen McClung, who's now deceased, and Jeff Lord, who practices in San Antonio, both got out of the Corps.
I elected to stay in.
Randy Doran over in B-1 was accepted and stayed in.
And one, I believe it was one other guy in the Corps that got out of the Corps that accepted.
The rest of them I'd known that were civilian students.
How did you let your family know that good news?
Oh, I gave them a call, and I remember my dad's pretty quiet and mild-mannered, and I said, Dad, I got accepted to vet school, and he said, well, that's real nice.
I'll never forget, you know, that's, you know, Grandpa, he's about as excited as he gets.
That's real nice.
Good, I'm proud of you.
That's about it, you know, but they were...
They were pleased.
Did any upperclassmen who was in vet school give you any advice then or before you got the next fall?
No, I didn't really know any.
I guess I knew one guy that was actually in vet school at the time, and he thought it would be a good idea that I get out of the Corps.
And I didn't do that.
And I'm glad I didn't, because I didn't need to.
Other than that, I didn't know anything about vet school until I got there.
All right.
So you go home for the summer, come back in the fall.
Right.
And vet school began at about the same time as...
Right.
About the same time I got back in time to start my core activities, and I think I had an extra day or two.
I'd bought a car that summer.
I needed to have a car to get out to the vet school, so I bought my first car.
I used Mach 1 Mustang.
And...
started going out and going to classes.
Describe how you and the other members of that first-year class, how were you welcomed?
Was there an opening event?
There was of some kind.
They had a thing early in the fall, just a welcome to the freshman class in one of the big amphitheaters.
They had some little finger food, I think.
That was about it.

now i've heard that al price used to give a lecture about how to pronounce the word how to pronounce and spell veterinarian and i can remember we called him slick al but he he got up and he said v e t e r i n a r i a n you will learn to pronounce it properly and you will learn to spell it
before you leave this class or you will fail vet school.
It is not negotiable.
I'll never forget that.
And to this day, I meet people, I sit on this national council on education for veterinary school and accreditation, and I'm the number of people that can't pronounce veterinary.
At Missouri.
And I was very close to the vet school up there.
Because, see, I was the chairman of the search committee that brought George Shelton here from there.
Right.
And then, unknown to me, when I was about to be interviewed up there, they put the president of the Alumni Association, University of Missouri, on the search committee.
Not a bad idea.
He saw that I had an A&M connection.
So he called up the fellow that he called Uncle George because his dad, as a vet faculty member, had office next to George Shelton for 21 years.
And said, tell me about this guy, da, da, da.
And then see Richard Adams.
was on the faculty and dean, and then he became dean up there while I was still up there, so a lot of... Now, what were you doing in Missouri?
I was a chancellor up there.
You were chancellor, okay.
Either you were president or... Well, the terminology is reversed up there.
Chancellor runs the campus.
Okay, because you left and you were president at UTEP and chancellor at Missouri, okay.
Because I visited with Richard Adams when he was still at Missouri when we were doing our accreditation stuff a good bit.
And see, when I got there, the vet school was on probation.
Right, a facilities issue.
Yeah.
And I got the fellow that sat on my left for 15 years that had a fair amount of money from the beer business in St. Louis.
And he made a big gift that helped a great deal.
That's what I heard.
I'm to do the commencement speech at the vet school this spring.
Wonderful.
And when we dedicated the Clivesdale Hall, as they happened to name it, the senior young lady
and speaking for the students.

She said, and in summary, Mr. Bush, what I want to assure you is that on behalf of all of the graduates of this vet school from now and in the future, I promise you we will do everything in our power to see that your profit
is very good from Anheuser-Busch.
Drink that Budweiser.
So did you turn to anybody before that fall semester, any practicing veterinarian or anything?
I had never worked for a veterinarian, hardly knew one.
And I went to Colorado.
Worked horses and fly fished and did my deal.
Nope.
And I'd been around medicine, of course, all my life with my dad's practice, but didn't.
I was ready to go.
And again, I didn't have a clinical, this is what I've got to do type thing.
Instead, I knew that I had a plan right after school.
Again, the war's still going on.
I took an early commission.
When I would graduate from professional school, I would go on active duty as a captain.
So I knew that I'd be going into the Air Force for a couple years minimum right out of vet school.
And as it turns out, I got an Air Force health profession scholarship greatly aided by my participation in the Corps that paid out vet school.
I was getting $400 a month back then just to go to vet school.
So when I left here, I owed no money.
I was in great shape.
You just introduced us to the first year program in vet, the first semester in veterinary medicine.
What kind of courses?
Basic courses, basic medicine courses and anatomy.
Everybody remembers freshman anatomy.
We also had a biochemistry course taught over here on the main campus.
The anatomy
It's all memorization.
It's rote memorization back then, but it had to be done.
I remember one of our colleagues that was real pushy-grabby, and he would come to a table of bones, and if you had one in your hand, he'd grab it out of your hand.
You know, because he wanted it.
You know, he was going to learn.
His name was Mike Norton.
And Mike grabbed the wrong bone from the wrong guy one time and got laid out right over an anatomy table, right there in the vet school.
That put an end to the grabbies.
Vet school was pretty, it was a new experience.
I was still in the Corps, but I would spend my days with mostly, all of them older students.
I was the youngest in the class, but all older, many of whom at least close to half had come from other institutions.
that many of them knew nothing about A&M.
One of my closest friends was, we still had 10 contract students from Louisiana, Paul Drake, big old coon ass from Ponchatoula, and he would just call me C.T., Corturd.
And with his coon ass he'd say, hey C.T., but we got along fine.
They all laughed, and every once in a while I'd have my uniform on, and they'd really get a kick out of that.
But it was all in good fun.

And two of us, Randy Dorn over in B1 and myself in Squadron 6, two of us stayed in the Corps, and we would march to chow in our white scrub suits because we had to get on to vet school in the mornings and get back in time for formation.
And it worked okay.
So you lived in the Corps area, went to morning chow,
Then quickly hurried over.
Went to the vet school, got in the car.
Vet school all day.
Right.
And there was a snack bar, and we'd eat over there and snack on something over there, and then come home in the evening for evening formation.
And it worked pretty well, and it wasn't too bad.
Compare the rigor of the courses first year in vet school compared to what you'd had freshman and sophomore year, undergraduate.
In some, they're a lot more focused, obviously, but, and I would say they were not any more rigorous than my honors colloquia.
They really were not.
They were just more focused towards where I was heading.
And I had, and I was taking a heavier load.
And you were there all day long.
All day long, right.
Did you sometimes go back at night?
Sure.
And of course, transportation was a big thing.
But now I had wheels, so going for evening formation and then if we had something on at the school at night or I needed to be in the vet school library, I would go back over if I needed to.
as a senior then as a, well as a second year student then, when I was a senior in the Corps, they were starting to get into clinical rotations and things I needed to be there for.
But it was okay, it worked alright, it was doable.
Looking back on it now, were there some important teachers, courses that first year in vet school?
Everybody has favorite professors and things.
I liked, Mike Tatum taught histology and understood the core and was very encouraging.
You know, stay, go do, how is it, fine.
I think the majority of the professors, I remember Dr. Miliff, I disrespected him because he was old and he'd been there.
And that was neat.
I don't think, what other?
Some were team-taught, so I don't recall.
But for some reason, Mike Tatum sticks out as being just very much a pleasant gentleman.
And Dr. Jim Anderson, physiology, pharmacology, I don't know if it was first year, but he and...
Dr. Clark and others were just, and Dr. Gleiber were real class people.
I didn't take a like their courses, but they were so pleasant, such true gentleman scholars, true scientists.
They were cut above the average.
They were neat people.
And the dropout or flunkout rate in vet school was quite low.
Very low.
I think we lost a couple students, probably three or four, and then they were replaced early on.
Were there women in your classes?
We had six.
How were they treated?
With some respect, but not a whole lot.
They were
If there were one or two that were, they got along pretty well and they were okay, and there were one or two that had a chip on their shoulder and they caught hell every day.
It never let up.
And I presume they had not been A&M undergraduates.
I know two of them had as married students.
The others came from outside, near as I remember.
I'm pretty sure, it was only six, and I think four of them came from outside, two of them had been undergraduate but were married.
Were there any black students?
No, there wasn't one in any of the classes while I was there.
But it was not officially segregated.
No, no, there just weren't.
There were only four blacks in my class in the corps total.
There were no blacks on the A&M football team until Hume McElroy came to play when I was a junior.
All right, let's jump back on that.
As far as you were aware, those four blacks in the corps, how were they treated?
Treated well.
I don't, there was no, again, it was pretty, you know, colloquial part of the world to a point, but I don't think there was any problems.
The two that had the roughest go were Fish Taylor and Fish Webster that were in Spider D. Their problems stemmed not because they were black, but because of Spider D and the horrible attrition rate.
And to this day, I can remember, because Fish Taylor had such a loud voice,
other upperclassmen picking on him all over the campus and I can remember being in the academic building in history and hearing somebody talking or listening to Fish Taylor answer to somebody

and then Humpett because he was in Spider D and I and of course they both flunked out but so did and that was the end of Spider D that was the last year at least in at that point in time in history they were disbanded after that year and went into C1 and C2 and were scattered around but now the the black students there were that stayed on I think by the time we were seniors I believe there were four
and graduated, all of them have done well.
All of them got four-year degrees and did fine.
Like typists, this is not, don't need to add this in, but I've told people here that blacks had a much easier time
being the pioneers here than the first women did.
There's no question.
It was way harder for women than it was for blacks.
Oh, there's no question.
None whatsoever.
And Fred McClure is a superb example of that.
So you were an unusual person in being in the core
and being in vet school at the same time, and were there any times that you recall that first year particularly when you had to make a choice of which do you do?
Yeah, I guess I was in Ross Volunteers and we had rifle drill every evening.
And there were times that I had, there was three nights a week that was difficult for me to get back in time for rifle drill.
And so I had to get into my fatigues and get out to rifle drill, and because I was late, I always had to run extra.
And there was not a thing I could do about it unless I cut my vet school class short, and I couldn't do that, so I just did the running.
And I'd had my knee surgery, and so my knee was a constant pain and problem, and so I hobbled through the RVs, but it was worth it.
It was fun.
And you were selected as an RV at the end of your sophomore year?
or at the beginning of the junior, whenever that happens.
I haven't recorded this before.
How does one become an RV?
Do you apply?
I think you must apply, or either that or you're asked to apply.
I don't recall.
I think you're asked, I don't know, I believe you're asked to apply.
Did you turn in letters of recommendation or anything?
I don't recall any letters of recommendation.
I think you stand on, there's a selection committee, I assume, and I really, I don't remember,

it's basically you know if you want to do this go you know you're you're up you know would you be interested type deal and and then go on and stand on the merits of whatever you've done your first two years who the selection committee was no was it other cadets it would have been it would have been uh rv uh rvs from the year before and how many are selected we had three platoons of uh approximately 20 per platoon i want to say approximately 60.
So about half of them were juniors?
No, those were all juniors, and then you had a handful of, you had two, four, six, you probably had about 12 senior advisors, and that was it.
Or you had your platoon leaders and the first sergeant, and that was it.
So you had 10 or 12 seniors, and that was it.
But only two were active with each company with the drill, with each platoon drill in the afternoon.
So really only six after seniors that were there on a day-to-day basis.
How did you learn you'd been selected?
Don't recall.
I don't remember.
I was the only one.
Let's see.
I guess I was the only one in our outfit.
There was one other, Kort Koontz, no two, Kenny Hill, Kort Koontz, and myself.
Kort had come over from squadron eight because there were no ag kids in it.
So the three of us were selected.
And I remember they had a little banquet at the MSC where they handed us our yellow crapper cords.
And that was the last fun time we had as juniors.
Well, that's not true, but that was back before drill started.
And you were in the RVs two years.
Just one year as a junior, and only you could go out to drill as a senior if you wanted to, but only a few that had the time that could stay on.
What were the highlights of being an RV member that year?
Oh, two things.
One was the governor's inauguration.
It was Preston Smith, and the main thing was going to Austin.

being an RV there, and we were in the, I guess we were in Senate chambers, or the House, we were in a smaller room, it wasn't full chambers, but the microphone was on, and we didn't realize it, and we were getting dressed, and we were cutting up in there, and it was being broadcast all over the Capitol.
Did anybody attempt any goof-ups or jokes?
Oh yeah, we had, and I can't remember,
